Cyber Angel Benten - I would play more but Drytron got it limited, this card if ever brought back to 3 is certainly worth playing at 3. 2 ofs: Etoile Cyber - Just Playing it as tribute fodder. Cyber Angel Nashata - Let's me take control of a monster my opponent controls after it's been sent to the GY when it been properly Summoned. 3 ofs: Cyber Tutabon - Lets me grab a Ritual Spell when tributed so it's just there for the recycling. Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring - Average hand trap used in most decks. Cyber Petit Angel - On Summon lets me grab a Machine Angel Ritual or Cyber Angel depending on what I need. Cyber Egg Angel - Lets me add a Ritual Sanctuary or Machine Angel Spell from my Deck to my hand. Cyber Angel Vrash - The major Wincon of the Deck, lets me pop all monsters opponent controls Special Summoned from the Extra Deck plus gains an extra Attack as well as having a pop negate. Cyber Angel Dakini - On Summon forces your opponent to send a monster to their GY, has a recycling effect, and can make all Rituals inflict piercing battle damage. Cyber Angel Izana - Forces your opponent to send a monster they control to the GY, lets me attack again when it destroys a monster by battle, Has a built-in pop when the opponent targets a Cyber Angel. Cyber Angel Idaten - Lets me give all my Ritual monsters an extra 1000 in stats when tributed. Incarnated Machine Angel - Makes all my Cyber Angels unable to be destroyed by battle, and lets me Ritual Summon whenever I take damage. Machine Angel Ritual - My only Ritual Spell and helps protect my Cyber Angel from card effect destruction. Merciful Machine Angel - Lets me draw 2 cards by tributing a Cyber Angel Ritual monster. You don't really need cards to stay in your graveyard with this deck, just keep Prank-Kids Dropsies there 3x Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring - My favorite hand trap 3x Infinite Impermanence - My second favorite hand trap (better than effect veiler, fight me) 1x Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity - A zexal that you can summon on your opponent’s turn pretty easily. All you need to end on is Crystron Halqifibrax, a level 2 Adamancipator, and Borreload Savage Dragon. Pretty easy to summon, too 1x Ningirsu the World Chalice Warrior - Dragoon removal, pretty much 1x Naturia Barkion - It's in the side deck, but this card destroys trap decks. deck_excerpt: Zombie Madness retrain that feels old school but plays pretty strong
deck_description:
I loved Zombie Madness when I was a kid, and I wanted to recreate the feeling of beating into your opponent with big beatsticks like back then with Vampire Genesis. This time, however, the boss monster is Endless Decay. This guy takes half of your opponent's current life points as its ATK points, but even better, it can be Special and Normal Summoned with relative ease. For example, here's some plays you can do:
  • Discard Mezuki and Endless Decay from an opponent's Hand Destruction, then use Mezuki's effect to Special Summon Endless Decay, activating his ability
  • Special Summon Endless Decay from the GY with Book of Life or Monster Reborn
  • Special Summon from the Deck with Pyramid Turtle's ability
  • Special Summon with Call of the Mummy
  • Normal Summon with just one tribute
  • ...and more!
This deck includes some dead draw cards like Mage Power and Axe of Despair, but in all honesty I don't tend to brick with this deck. You consistently get Endless Decay out without much of a hitch. Even if you have an opponent with backrow destruction, it doesn't really matter. Mezuki and Pyramid Turtle do just fine. Get Endless Decay out as soon as possible, best if they have 8000 LP. Since it takes half of your opponent's LP as its ATK, you really need to rush Endless Decay. It isn't too much of a problem, but still- there have been times when I didn't have a solid win condition because I couldn't get it out fast enough. I sideboarded Nobleman of Crossout because it was a decent enough card to keep but not always the best draw to have and Hand Destruction for the discard and draw 2. Twin Twisters would probably be better than MST, but for the sake of Zombie Madness I wanted to keep it as close to the original deck (and as close to the original idea of the deck- getting huge beatsticks for massive damage) as possible. The Extra Deck could use some work, but for now it works. If you have any suggestions, let me know!

deck_excerpt: The future of Dragon Link (or other combo decks) ?!?!
deck_description: (This is a test build to Brave D-link.) (I got inspired by the brave tokken prank kids list which won an 52 player event and went 8-0.) This version of d-link uses the "Brave Tokken" archetype which gets released in the Grand Creators as a 1 card omni negate engine.  You basically use the Aquamancer to get "Rite of Aramesia", which will give you an "Brave Tokken" and the countinous Spell "Jpurney of Destiny", this will search the "Wandering Gryphon Rider" and if you summon a monster you can add the "Dracoback the Dragon Steed" to your hand. This are basically a free omni negate and a free discard which also can chain block. Gryphons summon is a quick effect, so you can actually activate something like chaos space and chain gryphon to it. And Dracoback has a gy effect which triggers if it gets discarded, let's say by a dragon ravine, so you can discard it for ravine and send absorouter and then you can chain block the absorouter. This allows d-link to play even better through handtraps and the only downsides are that you can't activate the on field effects of a normal summoned monster (Seyvert and Chamber) and you only have 3 monster zones you can play with, which sounds like a good pay off to me. And you can play around the first restriction by just using stuff like world legacy guardragon or pisty to get the normal summoned monsters back. Oh and there is even more, you can actually use the tokken as synchro/link material, so if you need one you can just use the tokken (which is a level 4 btw).
Just have fun.

deck_excerpt: A poor attempt at making Zefra playable.
deck_description:
Terrible Zefra deck, born out of boredom and a desperation to make Zefra somewhat playable. This isn't even Zefra, it's just a bunch of crutches that can carry the rest of this useless deck to a win. Your main opener is a Halqifibrax combo: Keep in mind that Zefraxi turns any 'Zefra' monster on board into a tuner if it's Pendulum Summoned.
  1. Get a monster and a tuner on board, and only those 2 monsters. Resist the urge to pendulum summon everything out of hand. If you're desperate, the handtraps are tuners.
  2. Summon Crystron Halqifibrax, activate its trigger effect to summon Deskbot 001 from deck.
  3. Link for Mecha-Phantom Beast Auroradon, summon 3 tokens, then summon 001 from GY.
  4. Using a token and 001, summon Herald of the Arc Light.
  5. Using Auroradon's 2nd effect, tribute 2 tokens to summon Mecha-Phantom Beast Coltwing. Coltwing effect for 2 tokens, and summon 001 from GY again.
  6. 001 and token to summon Cupid Pitch, choose to increase level.
  7. Level 5 Cupid Pitch and token for Borreload Savage Dragon, equip Halq. Use Cupid Pitch's effect to search Hop Ear Squadron.
During your Opponent's turn, you can use Hop Ear in order to Synchro Summon for Metaphys Horus for an additional negate. Keep in mind that Metaphys Horus' negate is an on-summon trigger, so it will not go on the same chain. In the case that 001 is negated by either Ghost Belle or Skull Meister after Auroradon summons 3 tokens, you can either: use Auroradon to tribute 2 tokens and summon Coltwing, and summon the 001. From here, you make Cupid Pitch and do the standard combo to make a Borrelsavage. Then, you can use the Hop Ear you searched to summon Ravenous Crocodragon Archethys at the start of your Opponent's MP1 using Hop Ear and Coltwing. OR: Choose to reduce the level of Cupid Pitch, and then synchro summon Ravenous Crocodragon with 3 materials to draw 2 cards. Then use Hop Ear to make Horus during Opponent's turn. The above combo described actually has absolutely NOTHING to do with Zefra. It is deadup a generic Halqifibrax combo. You can probably use it in anything you damn well please. Some questionable decisions:  Fusion Destiny: The new Destroy Phoenix Enforcer is one hell of a crutch. Alternatively, you can run the Dragoon + Verte package, which is still more potent than D.P.E., but people are more prone to immediately scoop upon Dragoon than Phoenix Enforcer. Nekroz of Unicore: This card is literally a brick in 90% of situations. It is a free search off Herald of Arc Light if the Halq combo goes through, but in all honesty, it is best to remove it. Of all the games I have played where Unicore ended up in hand, it ended up as discard fodder every single time. Crossout Designator: Halq combo immediately dies to handtraps. Less so to Ghost Belle and Meister, but definitely gets rolled by Ash, Imperm, Veiler, Nibiru and Gamma. The random mash of handtraps can come in handy going 2nd too, the ratios are yours to screw around with. Zefra Metaltron: He is only here because he's the Zefra link and he looks cool. There is probably something better to run than this horrible thing. Actual Zefra Stuff. Your best card in the deck is Zefraniu, Secret of the Yang Zing. He quite literally searches your entire deck on Pendulum Summon or destruction while in a monster zone. If you can't go into any crazy combo, and can only summon a Zefrainu, the move is to search Nine Pillars of the Yang Zing off Zefraniu. This allows you to search another card during your Opponent's turn when Nine Pillars destroys Zefraniu. From there, you can set up for next turn, or search for Zefra War, which activates from hand if you have 2 Zefras on scale. If possible, destroy your Field Spell with Zefra War. If you have Zefra Providence in your GY, then feel free to target your own scale and protect it if you don't have the field spell. Or just straight up blow up your scale if you're that desperate. Zefraath is exclusively a scale. His effect is dogshit useless. He tributes your ENTIRE BOARD from the E/D, so he summons himself into the Extra Monster Zone. If you haven't noticed yet, that renders his second effect to allow a second Pendulum Summon that turn entirely null and void. Yeah. Master Rule 4 has not been kind to Pendulums. If it's any consolation, Zefraath is probably your best scale, and you always want Zefraath on one of the scales. Yeah, that's about it. If you have any advice, please do tell. With Electrumite in jail, Pendulums are in a sad, sad, desperate state. Please send help.
